s usually the Scottish form, that with the intrusive <i>-p-</i> being English. Both forms are common in Ireland. The surname <i>Thompson</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen   and of its Swedish cognate <b>Thomsson</b>. Compare   Thomson  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Walker","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin an occupational name for a fuller, Old English <i>wealcere</i>, a derivative of <i>wealcan</i> ‘to walk, tread’ the fulling process involved treading cloth in vats of lye."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Walker Thomson was born about 1563, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John Thomson."},"et":{"abt 1563–":"umbes 1563–Surnud","1566–Male":"1566–Surnud","1591–Male":"1591–Surnud","1563–Female":"1563–Surnud","17 Jan 1591":"17. jaanuar 1591","1566":"1566","1563":"1563","1591":"1591","abt 1563":"umbes 1563","of Dunfermline, Fife, Scot.":"Dunfermline, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dunfermline, Fife, Scot.":"Dunfermline, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1563–":"noin 1563–Kuollut","1566–Male":"1566–Kuollut","1591–Male":"1591–Kuollut","1563–Female":"1563–Kuollut","17 Jan 1591":"17. tammikuuta 1591","1566":"1566","1563":"1563","1591":"1591","abt 1563":"noin 1563","of Dunfermline, Fife, Scot.":"Dunfermline, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dunfermline, Fife, Scot.":"Dunfermline, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt ku